[1
Date: Fri, 11 Jun 1999
From: Chan Yow Cheong
ProMED-mail Regional Moderator for Asia
Source: Agence France-Presse ex New Straits Times, 11 Jun 1999 [edited

Indonesian authorities were unlikely to ban European food imports amid a
scare over contaminated Belgian products, but were still mulling the
situation, the health ministry said in reports Friday.
"We are still discussing the issue with the animal husbandry section of the
ministry of agriculture, which is actually in charge of the matter. We will
soon issue a decision," health ministry spokeswoman Mariani told the
Jakarta Post.
However, Indonesia did not import a significant amount of farm and dairy
products from Europe, she added. "It would be unlikely for Indonesia to
take an extreme action, such as banning or destroying European foods here.
However, we advise all concerned parties to exercise caution until a final
decision is made."
China on Thursday added its name to the list of Asian countries restricting
Belgian - and sometimes European - food imports, including Thailand,
Singapore, South Korea, Malaysia, and the Philippines. Hong Kong has also
issued a ban.
But the European Union's senior diplomat in southeast Asia Michael
Caillouet has called on Asian governments to lift import bans, saying there
was no evidence European products were tainted with potentially
cancer-causing dioxins.
Caillouet told reporters in Bangkok that the contamination of Belgian
products had been isolated to one animal feed producer in Belgium and
brought under control.
